🏗 3. Your actual Power Query steps (I’ll give you the full code)

After you import the Excel file in Power BI → Transform Data → Select the sheet → then apply this.

Here’s the ready-to-paste M code (Power Query):

let
    Source = Excel.Workbook(File.Contents("C:\YourPath\Feedback.xlsx"), null, true),
    Sheet = Source{[Item="2025 Mock data", Kind="Sheet"]}[Data],
    PromotedHeaders = Table.PromoteHeaders(Sheet, [PromoteAllScalars=true]),

    // Identify non-score columns (the first ones)
    NonScoreColumns = {"Date of Course", "Course Name", "FunctionBU", "Experience Level"},

    // All other columns (Q1, Q2, Q3, ... Qn)
    ScoreColumns = List.Difference(Table.ColumnNames(PromotedHeaders), NonScoreColumns),

    // Unpivot Q columns
    Unpivoted = Table.Unpivot(PromotedHeaders, ScoreColumns, "Question", "Score"),

    // Convert data types
    ChangedTypes = Table.TransformColumnTypes(Unpivoted,{
        {"Date of Course", type date},
        {"Course Name", type text},
        {"FunctionBU", type text},
        {"Experience Level", type text},
        {"Question", type text},
        {"Score", Int64.Type}
    })

in
    ChangedTypes

🎉 After this, you will have the perfect clean data model.


